22%3Ereferred%20%3C%2Fa%3Ethe%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.scobserver.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2021%2F09%2FKishore_Wangkhemcha_v._Union_of_India1.pdf%5C%22%3Epetitions%3C%2Fa%3E%20challenging%20Section%20124A%20IPC%2C%20making%20sedition%20an%20offence%2C%20to%20a%20constitution%20bench.%3Cspan%3E%C2%A0%20%C2%A0%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EIn%20the%20same%20order%2C%20the%20three-judge%20bench%20rejected%20the%20government%E2%80%99s%20plea%20to%20defer%20the%20hearing%20in%20light%20of%20the%20newly%20introduced%20criminal%20law%20Bill%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fprsindia.org%2Ffiles%2Fbills_acts%2Fbills_parliament%2F2023%2FBharatiya_Nyaya_Sanhita%2C_2023.pdf%5C%22%3Ethe%20Bharatiya%20Nyaya%20Sanhita%3C%2Fa%3E.%3Cspan%3E%C2%A0%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThe%20petitioners%20include%20Major%20General%20S.G.%20Vombatkere%20(the%20lead%20petitioner%20in%20the%20case)%3B%20two%20journalists%2C%20Kishore%20Wangkhemcha%20and%20Kanhaiya%20Lal%20Shukla%20(both%20having%20suffered%20by%20the%20wrongful%20application%20of%20law%20by%20the%20Manipur%20and%20Chhattisgarh%20governments%20respectively)%3B%20the%20Editors%20Guild%20of%20India%3B%20Journalists%E2%80%99%20Association%20of%20Assam%3B%20Arun%20Shourie%3B%20the%20People%E2%80%99s%20Union%20for%20Civil%20Liberties%3B%20Mahua%20Moitra%2C%20MP%20from%20the%20Trinamool%20Congress%3B%20Patricia%20Mukhim%2C%20editor%20of%20the%20%3Cem%3EShillong%20Times%3C%2Fem%3E%3B%20and%20Anil%20Chamadia%2C%20chairman%20of%20the%20Media%20Studies%20Group.%3Cspan%3E%C2%A0%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3ESection%20124A%20seeks%20to%20punish%20one%20found%20guilty%20of%20sedition%20with%20imprisonment%20for%20life%2C%20to%20which%20a%20fine%20may%20be%20added%2C%20or%20with%20imprisonment%20which%20may%20extend%20to%20three%20years%2C%20to%20which%20a%20fine%20may%20be%20added%2C%20or%20with%20a%20fine.%3Cspan%3E%C2%A0%3C%2Fspan%3EIt%20defines%20sedition%20as%20bringing%20or%20attempting%20to%20bring%20into%20hatred%20or%20contempt%20or%20exciting%20or%20attempting%20to%20excite%20disaffection%20towards%20the%20Government%20established%20by%20law%20in%20India.%3Cspan%3E%C2%A0%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3ECJI%2C%20Chandrachud%20observed%20%E2%80%93%20while%20speaking%20at%20the%20convocation%20ceremony%20at%20the%20Maharashtra%20National%20Law%20University%2C%20Aurangabad%20%E2%80%93%20that%20in%20cases%20involving%20colonial-era%20laws%20like%20sedition%2C%20the%20question%20of%20whether%20justice%20is%20served%20depends%20on%20those%20wielding%20power.%20For%20the%20petitioners%20challenging%20afresh%20the%20validity%20of%20Section%20124A%20%E2%80%93%20a%20colonial%20law%2C%20the%20CJI%E2%80%99s%20observation%20is%20of%20significance%2C%20as%20they%20expect%20the%20proposed%20constitution%20bench%20to%20not%20leave%20the%20question%20of%20justice%20in%20sedition%20cases%20to%20the%20vicissitudes%20of%20politics.%20%3Cspan%3E%C2%A0%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3E%3Ci%3EThe%20Wire%3C%2Fi%3E%20breaks%20down%20the%20issues%20in%20reference%20to%20the%20challenge%20to%20the%20sedition%20law%2C%20and%20also%20the%20import%20of%20what%20the%20CJI%20observed.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3E%3Cb%3EWhy%20did%20the%20three-judge%20bench%20refer%20the%20case%20to%20a%20larger%20bench%3F%3C%2Fb%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EIn%201962%2C%20in%20%3Ci%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fglobalfreedomofexpression.columbia.edu%2Fcases%2Fnath-singh-v-bihar%2F%23%3A~%3Atext%3DThe%2520Supreme%2520Court%2520of%2520India%2Cfor%2520the%2520Forward%2520Communist%2520Party.%5C%22%3EKedar%20Nath%20Singh%20vs%20State%20of%20Bihar%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20%3C%2Fi%3Ethe%20Supreme%20Court%E2%80%99s%20five-judge%20bench%20upheld%20the%20constitutionality%20of%20Section%20124A%20IPC%20on%20the%20ground%20that%20it%20is%20a%20valid%20restriction%20on%20the%20right%20to%20freedom%20of%20expression%20only%20when%20the%20words%20are%20intended%20to%20disturb%20public%20peace%20by%20violence.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3ETherefore%2C%20the%20petitions%20challenging%20afresh%20the%20constitutionality%20of%20Section%20124A%20%E2%80%93%20on%20grounds%20not%20anticipated%20in%20%3Ci%3EKedar%20Nath%20Singh%3C%2Fi%3E%20%E2%80%93%20must%2C%20in%20keeping%20with%20judicial%20propriety%2C%20be%20heard%20by%20a%20bench%20of%20equal%20strength.%20It%20is%20very%20likely%20that%20the%20five-judge%20bench%2C%20to%20be%20constituted%20by%20the%20CJI%2C%20will%20refer%20the%20new%20petitions%20to%20a%20seven-judge%20bench%2C%20which%20will%20then%20hear%20arguments%20for%20and%20against%20declaring%20Section%20124A%20as%20unconstitutional.%20In%20view%20of%20the%20Supreme%20Court%E2%80%99s%20five-judge%20bench%E2%80%99s%20decision%20in%20%3Ci%3EKedar%20Nath%20Singh%3C%2Fi%3E%2C%20only%20a%20seven-judge%20bench%20can%20declare%20the%20provision%20as%20unconstitutional.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3ESenior%20advocate%20Kapil%20Sibal%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.scobserver.in%2Freports%2Fconstitutionality-of-sedition-law-day-6-cji-led-bench-refers-challenge-to-a-constitution-bench-of-at-least-5-judges%2F%5C%22%3Estressed%3C%2Fa%3E%20the%20urgent%20need%20to%20hear%20the%20challenge%20against%20Section%20124A%20citing%20several%20%E2%80%9Cpending%20prosecutions%E2%80%9D%20against%20individuals.%20According%20to%20data%20captured%20by%20%3Cem%3EArticle-14%3C%2Fem%3E%20in%20the%20report%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fsedition.article-14.com%2F%5C%22%3E%E2%80%98A%20Decade%20of%20Darkness%E2%80%99%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20867%20cases%20under%20the%20Section%20were%20filed%20against%2013%2C306%20individuals%20in%20the%20country.%20Further%2C%20as%20the%20%3Cem%3ETimes%20of%20India%3C%2Fem%3E%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ftimesofindia.indiatimes.com%2Findia%2Fof-548-held-just-12-in-7-cases-convicted%2Farticleshow%2F91451710.cms%5C%22%3Ereported%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20citing%20data%20compiled%20by%20the%20National%20Crime%20Records%20Bureau%20(NCRB)%3A%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3E%E2%80%9C%3Ci%3EA%20total%20356%20cases%20of%20sedition%20%E2%80%94%20as%20defined%20under%20Section%20124%20were%20registered%20and%20548%20persons%20arrested%20between%202015%20and%202020.%20However%2C%20just%2012%20persons%20arrested%20in%20seven%20sedition%20cases%20were%20convicted%20in%20this%20six-year%20period%3C%2Fi%3E.%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EAlthough%20Sibal%20suggested%20that%20the%20constitutionality%20of%20sedition%20can%20either%20be%20evaluated%20by%20a%20five-judge%20bench%20or%20a%20division%20bench%20of%20the%20Supreme%20Court%20can%20hear%20the%20case%20without%20a%20reference%2C%20the%20three-judge%20bench%20decided%20in%20favour%20of%20referring%20it%20to%20a%20five-judge%20bench.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3E%3Cb%3EWhat%20are%20the%20fresh%20grounds%20raised%20by%20the%20petitioners%3F%3C%2Fb%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3ESection%20124A%20penalises%20individuals%20who%20%E2%80%9Cexcite%20disaffection%E2%80%9D%20against%20a%20%E2%80%9Cgovernment%20established%20by%20law%E2%80%9D.%3Cb%3E%C2%A0%3C%2Fb%3EIn%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Findiankanoon.org%2Fdoc%2F111867%2F%5C%22%3E%3Ci%3EKedar%20Nath%20Singh%3C%2Fi%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20the%20Supreme%20Court%20observed%20that%20the%20%E2%80%9Ccontinued%20existence%20of%20the%20Government%20established%20by%20law%20is%20an%20essential%20condition%20of%20the%20stability%20of%20the%20State%E2%80%9D.%20The%20petitioners%20in%20%3Ci%3ES.G.%20Vombatkere%20%3C%2Fi%3Erejected%20this%20idea.%20They%20contended%20that%20the%20terms%20%E2%80%9Cstate%E2%80%9D%20and%20%E2%80%9Cgovernment%20established%20by%20law%E2%80%9D%20are%20separate.%20In%20essence%2C%20they%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fmain.sci.gov.in%2Fsupremecourt%2F2021%2F14059%2F14059_2021_1_9_46876_Order_12-Sep-2023.pdf%5C%22%3Eexpressed%3C%2Fa%3E%20the%20stance%20that%20a%20%E2%80%9Cdisaffection%E2%80%9D%20towards%20the%20government%20was%20not%20equivalent%20to%20%E2%80%9Cdisaffection%E2%80%9D%20towards%20the%20State%2C%20and%20that%20both%20terms%20have%20to%20be%20construed%20separately.%3Cspan%3E%C2%A0%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3ECJI%20Chandrachud%20noted%20during%20the%20hearing%20of%20the%20case%20on%20September%2012%20that%20the%20judgment%20in%3Cspan%3E%20the%C2%A0%3C%2Fspan%3E%3Ci%3EKedar%20Nath%20Singh%20%3C%2Fi%3Ecase%3Ci%3E%20%3C%2Fi%3Edid%20not%20distinguish%20between%20the%20state%20and%20government%20and%20construed%20these%20two%20words%20synonymously.%20As%20Article%2019(2)%20dealing%20with%20reasonable%20restrictions%20on%20freedom%20of%20expression%20uses%20the%20word%20%E2%80%9Cstate%E2%80%9D%2C%20rather%20than%20%E2%80%9Cgovernment%E2%80%9D%2C%20Section%20124A%2C%20as%20originally%20drafted%2C%20cannot%20be%20immune%20from%20challenge%20on%20the%20ground%20of%20being%20a%20reasonable%20restriction.%3Cspan%3E%C2%A0%20%3C%2Fspan%3EThe%20constraints%20imposed%20by%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.constitutionofindia.net%2Farticles%2Farticle-19-protection-of-certain-rights-regarding-freedom-of-speech-etc%2F%5C%22%3EArticle%2019(2)%3C%2Fa%3E%20(%E2%80%9C%3Ci%3ENothing%20in%20sub-clause%20(a)%20of%20clause%20(1)%20shall%20affect%20the%20operation%20of%20any%20existing%20law%2C%20or%20prevent%20the%20State%20from%20making%20any%20law%2C%20in%20so%20far%20as%20such%20law%20imposes%20reasonable%20restrictions%20on%20the%20exercise%20of%20the%20right%20conferred%20by%20the%20said%20sub-clause%20in%20the%20interests%20of%20the%20sovereignty%20and%20integrity%20of%20India%2C%20the%20security%20of%20the%20State%2C%20friendly%20relations%20with%20foreign%20States%2C%20public%20order%2C%20decency%20or%20morality%2C%20or%20in%20relation%20to%20contempt%20of%20court%2C%20defamation%20or%20incitement%20to%20an%20offence.%3C%2Fi%3E%E2%80%9D)%20will%20not%20apply%20to%20the%20provision%20if%20the%20bigger%20bench%20determines%20that%20the%20words%20%E2%80%9CState%E2%80%9D%20and%20%E2%80%9CGovernment%E2%80%9D%20are%20distinct.%20On%20this%20ground%20alone%2C%20Section%20124A%20can%20be%20declared%20as%20unconstitutional%2C%20and%20the%20judgment%20in%20%3Cem%3EKedar%20Nath%20Singh%3C%2Fem%3E%20set%20aside.%3Cspan%3E%C2%A0%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cdiv%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption%5C%22%3E%3Cimg%20sizes%3D%5C%22(max-width%3A%20709px)%2085vw%2C%20(max-width%3A%20909px)%2067vw%2C%20(max-width%3A%201362px)%2062vw%2C%20840px%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2021%2F03%2F02160522%2Fsedition.png%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20width%3D%5C%22895%5C%22%20srcset%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2021%2F03%2F02160522%2Fsedition.png%20895w%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2021%2F03%2F02160522%2Fsedition-300x160.png%20300w%5C%22%20class%3D%5C%22wp-image-513774%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22478%5C%22%3E%3Cp%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption-text%5C%22%3EIllustration%3A%20The%20Wire%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%20%3Cp%3E%3Cb%3EThe%20three-judge%20bench%20rejected%20the%20government%E2%80%99s%20plea%20to%20defer%20the%20hearing%20of%20the%20case%20in%20view%20of%20the%20new%20Bharatiya%20Nyaya%20Sanhita%20Bill%2C%20which%20purportedly%20repeals%20sedition%20as%20an%20offence.%20Why%3F%3C%2Fb%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThe%20Bharatiya%20Nyaya%20Sanhita%20Bill%20appears%20to%20do%20away%20with%20the%20offence%20of%20sedition%3B%20however%2C%20the%20Bill%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.hindustantimes.com%2Findia-news%2Fsedition-under-the-new-bharatiya-nyaya-sanhita-bill-2023-what-s-changed-101691751947093.html%5C%22%3Eretains%3C%2Fa%3E%20it%20with%20a%20more%20expansive%20definition%20of%20sedition%20as%20%E2%80%9Cacts%20endangering%20sovereignty%2C%20unity%20and%20integrity%20of%20India%E2%80%9D%20and%20includes%20within%20its%20ambit%20secession%2C%20armed%20rebellion%2C%20subversive%20activities%20and%20%E2%80%9Cencouraging%20feelings%20of%20separatist%20activities%E2%80%9D.%20The%20new%20provision%2C%20Section%20150%2C%20enhances%20the%20minimum%20punishment%20from%203%20to%207%20years%20imprisonment%20and%20is%20likely%20to%20be%2C%20if%20enacted%2C%20more%20draconian%20than%20the%20provision%20under%20challenge%20before%20the%20Supreme%20Court.%3Cspan%3E%C2%A0%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThe%20new%20provision%20drops%20the%20word%20%E2%80%9Cdisaffection%E2%80%9D%20and%20Explanation%201%2C%20which%20defines%20disaffection%20as%20disloyalty%20and%20all%20feelings%20of%20enmity.%20However%2C%20it%20merges%20Explanations%202%20and%203%20to%20Section%20124A%20as%20follows%3A%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3E%E2%80%9C%3Ci%3EComments%20expressing%20disapprobation%20of%20the%20measures%2C%20or%20administrative%20or%20other%20action%20of%20the%20Government%20with%20a%20view%20to%20obtain%20their%20alteration%20by%20lawful%20means%20without%20exciting%20or%20attempting%20to%20excite%20the%20activities%20referred%20to%20in%20this%20section%E2%80%9D.%3C%2Fi%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3E%5BThe%20words%20%E2%80%9Cdo%20not%20constitute%20an%20offence%20under%20this%20section%E2%80%9D%20found%20in%20Explanations%202%20and%203%20to%20Section%20124A%20are%20ironically%20missing%20in%20Section%20150%20%E2%80%93%20which%20may%20be%20unintentional%5D%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThe%20three-judge%20bench%20took%20note%20of%20Sibal%E2%80%99s%20submission%20that%20Section%20150%20of%20the%20new%20Bill%20is%20more%20draconian%20than%20Section%20124A%2C%20and%20held%20that%20the%20new%20penal%20legislation%20brought%20in%20will%20not%20%E2%80%9Cobviate%20the%20need%20to%20adjudicate%20upon%20the%20constitutional%20validity%20of%20Section%20124A%E2%80%9D%20as%20penal%20legislations%20will%20not%20have%20a%20retrospective%20effect.%20Essentially%2C%20all%20pending%20prosecutions%20under%20Section%20124A%20will%20continue%20even%20after%20the%20new%20penal%20legislation%20comes%20into%20application.%20Additionally%2C%20the%20bench%20agreed%20with%20Sibal%20that%20as%20long%20as%20the%20statute%20continues%20to%20exist%2C%20its%20constitutionality%20needs%20to%20be%20examined%2C%20and%20if%20declared%20unconstitutional%2C%20all%20pending%20cases%20under%20the%20provision%20will%20automatically%20be%20dropped%20as%20the%20provision%20will%20be%20considered%20to%20never%20have%20existed.%3Cspan%3E%C2%A0%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3E%3Cb%3EFurthermore%2C%20the%20bench%20%3C%2Fb%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fmain.sci.gov.in%2Fsupremecourt%2F2021%2F14059%2F14059_2021_1_9_46876_Order_12-Sep-2023.pdf%5C%22%3E%3Cb%3Estated%3C%2Fb%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%3Cb%3E%20on%20September%2012%20that%20Section%20124A%20was%20a%20pre-constitutional%20enactment%20and%20thus%20does%20not%20carry%20the%20same%20presumption%20of%20constitutionality%20as%20carried%20by%20legislation%20that%20came%20into%20being%20after%20the%20enactment%20of%20the%20constitution.%20What%20is%20the%20doctrine%20of%20presumption%20of%20constitutionality%3F%3C%2Fb%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThe%20doctrine%20of%20presumption%20of%20constitutionality%20means%20that%20when%20a%20statute%20legislated%20by%20parliament%20is%20challenged%2C%20the%20judiciary%20shall%20defer%20to%20the%20legislature%20and%20the%20onus%20of%20proving%20the%20unconstitutionality%20of%20the%20provision%20rests%20on%20the%20petitioners.%3Cspan%3E%C2%A0%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EAs%20G.P.%20Singh%20writes%20in%20his%20book%2C%20%3Ci%3EPrinciples%20of%20Statutory%20Interpretation%3C%2Fi%3E%3A%20%E2%80%9CA%20statute%20is%20construed%20so%20as%20to%20make%20it%20effective%20and%20operative%20on%20the%20principle%20expressed%20in%20the%20maxim%20%E2%80%9Cut%20res%20magis%20valeat%20quam%20pereat%E2%80%9D.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThere%20is%2C%20therefore%2C%20a%20presumption%20that%20the%20legislature%20does%20not%20exceed%20its%20jurisdiction%2C%20and%20the%20burden%20of%20establishing%20that%20the%20Act%20is%20not%20within%20the%20competence%20of%20the%20legislature%2C%20or%20that%20it%20has%20transgressed%20other%20constitutional%20mandates%2C%20such%20as%20those%20relating%20to%20fundamental%20rights%2C%20is%20always%20on%20the%20person%20who%20challenges%20its%20vires.%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThus%20as%20per%20the%20doctrine%3A%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3E%3Ci%3E%E2%80%9CUnless%20it%20becomes%20clear%20beyond%20reasonable%20doubt%20that%20the%20legislation%20in%20question%20transgresses%20the%20limits%20laid%20down%20by%20the%20organic%20law%20of%20the%20Constitution%20it%20must%20be%20allowed%20to%20stand%20as%20the%20true%20expression%20of%20the%20national%20will.%3C%2Fi%3E%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EIn%20essence%2C%20in%20order%20to%20ensure%20that%20the%20full%20extent%20of%20a%20statute%20is%20realised%2C%20there%20exists%20a%20presumption%20that%20the%20legislature%20does%20not%20act%20in%20an%20%3Ci%3Eultra%20vires%3C%2Fi%3E%20manner%2C%20Additionally%2C%20since%20it%20is%20enacted%20by%20the%20legislature%20which%20comprises%20elected%20representatives%20of%20the%20people%2C%20it%20is%20considered%20a%20representation%20of%20the%20%E2%80%9Cnational%20will%E2%80%99.%20However%2C%20this%20idea%20only%20becomes%20applicable%20to%20legislations%20that%20came%20into%20enactment%20after%20the%20adoption%20of%20the%20constitution%20and%20not%20retrospectively.%3Cspan%3E%C2%A0%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThe%20three-judge%20bench%E2%80%99s%20drawing%20of%20attention%20to%20this%20aspect%20of%20Section%20124A%3Cspan%3E%C2%A0%20%E2%80%93%3C%2Fspan%3E%20being%20a%20colonial%20law%2C%20and%20therefore%2C%20not%20entitled%20to%20the%20protection%20of%20the%20doctrine%20of%20presumption%20of%20constitutionality%20%E2%80%93%20means%20that%20the%20burden%20of%20proving%20unconstitutionality%20would%20not%20be%20on%20the%20petitioners.%20Instead%2C%20it%20is%20the%20government%20which%20has%20to%20prove%20its%20constitutionality.%20This%20reversal%20of%20roles%20in%20constitutional%20litigation%20is%20likely%20to%20make%20the%20petitioners%E2%80%99%20challenge%20easier%2C%20although%20the%20court%20would%20look%20for%20other%20valid%20grounds%20to%20strike%20it%20down%20%E2%80%93%20rather%20than%20the%20simple%20fact%20of%20its%20having%20been%20enacted%20during%20the%20colonial%20era.%3Cspan%3E%C2%A0%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3E%3Cb%3EThe%20three-judge%20bench%20justified%20the%20reference%20to%20a%20larger%20bench%20on%20the%20ground%20that%20the%20bench%20in%20%3Ci%3EKedarnath%20Singh%20%3C%2Fi%3Ecould%20not%20have%20envisaged%20the%20developments%20in%20the%20law%20in%20later%20years%2C%20which%20would%20have%20a%20bearing%20on%20the%20validity%20of%20Section%20124A.%20What%20are%20those%20developments%20in%20law%2C%20which%20forced%20the%20bench%20to%20justify%20a%20relook%3F%3C%2Fb%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EPetitioners%20in%20S.G.%20Vombatkere%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fmain.sci.gov.in%2Fsupremecourt%2F2021%2F14059%2F14059_2021_1_9_46876_Order_12-Sep-2023.pdf%5C%22%3Eargued%3C%2Fa%3E%20that%20Section%20124A%20had%20only%20been%20tested%20on%20the%20touchstone%20of%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.constitutionofindia.net%2Farticles%2Farticle-19-protection-of-certain-rights-regarding-freedom-of-speech-etc%2F%5C%22%3EArticle%2019(1)(a)%3C%2Fa%3E%20(%E2%80%9C%3Ci%3Efreedom%20of%20speech%20and%20expression%E2%80%9D)%3C%2Fi%3E%20in%20the%20%3Ci%3EKedar%20Nath%20Singh%20%3C%2Fi%3Ejudgment.%20They%20submitted%20that%20it%20would%20be%20necessary%20to%20test%20its%20compliance%20with%20Articles%2014%20and%2021%20of%20the%20constitution%20considering%20the%20significant%20evolution%20of%20these%20articles%20since.%3Cspan%3E%C2%A0%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThe%20petitioners%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fmain.sci.gov.in%2Fsupremecourt%2F2021%2F14059%2F14059_2021_1_9_46876_Order_12-Sep-2023.pdf%5C%22%3Econtended%3C%2Fa%3E%20that%20section%20124A%20was%20made%20cognizable%20by%20the%20Code%20of%20Criminal%20Procedure%20in%201973%2C%20an%20additional%20ground%20to%20justify%20its%20reexamination%2C%20as%20the%20%3Ci%3EKedar%20Nath%20Singh%20%3C%2Fi%3Ebench%20held%20it%20constitutional%20when%20it%20was%20non-cognizable.%20As%20cognizable%20offences%20are%20crimes%20for%20which%20the%20police%20can%20make%20an%20arrest%20without%20a%20warrant%20or%20prior%20court%20permission%2C%20the%20instances%20of%20abuse%20of%20the%20provision%20against%20innocents%2C%20for%20whom%20the%20process%20itself%20became%20punishment%2C%20justified%20reconsideration%20of%20the%20%3Ci%3EKedar%20Nath%20Singh%3C%2Fi%3E%20judgment.%3Cspan%3E%C2%A0%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThe%20doctrine%20of%20proportionality%20is%20one%20which%20evolved%20in%20the%20post-%3Cem%3EKedar%20Nath%20Singh%3C%2Fem%3E%20years.%3Cspan%3E%C2%A0%20%3C%2Fspan%3EIt%20means%20that%20the%20measures%20taken%20must%20be%20reasonable%20with%20respect%20to%20the%20desired%20results.%3Cspan%3E%C2%A0%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThe%20three-judge%20bench%20observed%20on%20September%2012%20in%20its%20order%3A%3Cspan%3E%C2%A0%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3E%E2%80%9C%3Ci%3EThere%20was%20no%20challenge%20(in%20%3C%2Fi%3EKedar%20Nath%20Singh%3Ci%3E)%20on%20the%20ground%20that%20Section%20124A%20violated%20Article%2014%20nor%20did%20the%20Constitution%20Bench%20(in%20%3C%2Fi%3EKedar%20Nath%20Singh%3Ci%3E)%20have%20occasion%20to%20consider%20the%20validity%20of%20the%20provision%20against%20a%20constitutional%20challenge%20on%20the%20basis%20of%20Article%2014.%20The%20position%20as%20it%20has%20evolved%20in%20constitutional%20jurisprudence%20is%20that%20the%20fundamental%20rights%20do%20not%20exist%20in%20silos.%20There%20is%2C%20in%20other%20words%2C%20a%20coalescence%20of%20several%20of%20the%20rights%20protected%20by%20Part%20III.%20Article%2014%2C%20which%20presents%20an%20overarching%20principle%20of%20reasonableness%20permeates%20Articles%2019%20and%2021%20as%20well.%3C%2Fi%3E%E2%80%9D%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cdiv%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption%5C%22%3E%3Cimg%20sizes%3D%5C%22(max-width%3A%20709px)%2085vw%2C%20(max-width%3A%20909px)%2067vw%2C%20(max-width%3A%201362px)%2062vw%2C%20840px%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2020%2F09%2F15105244%2Fconstitution-of-india.png%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20width%3D%5C%22861%5C%22%20srcset%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2020%2F09%2F15105244%2Fconstitution-of-india.png%20861w%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2020%2F09%2F15105244%2Fconstitution-of-india-300x145.png%20300w%5C%22%20class%3D%5C%22wp-image-479273%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22417%5C%22%3E%3Cp%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption-text%5C%22%3EThe%20Constitution%20of%20India.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%20%3Cp%3E%3Cb%3EWhat%20does%20%E2%80%9Cfundamental%20rights%20do%20not%20exist%20in%20silos%E2%80%9D%20mean%3F%3C%2Fb%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EIn%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.casemine.com%2Fjudgement%2Fin%2F5609ab6fe4b014971140c79d%5C%22%3E%3Ci%3ERustom%20Cavasjee%20Cooper%20vs%20Union%20of%20India%3C%2Fi%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%20(1970)%2C%20popularly%20known%20as%20the%20bank%20nationalisation%20case%2C%20heard%20by%2011%20judges%2C%2014%20banks%20were%20proposed%20to%20be%20nationalised%20through%20an%20Ordinance.%20Cooper%20filed%20a%20writ%20petition%20under%20Article%2032%20alleging%20that%20the%20promulgation%20of%20the%20Ordinance%20had%20violated%20his%20fundamental%20rights.%20Cooper%20was%20not%20only%20the%20then%20director%20of%20the%20Central%20Bank%20of%20India%20Ltd.%2C%20but%20he%20also%20owned%20shares%20in%20the%20Bank%20of%20India%2C%20Bank%20of%20Baroda%2C%20and%20the%20Central%20Bank%20of%20India.%3Cspan%3E%C2%A0%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThe%20primary%20contribution%20of%20this%20case%20was%20the%20rejection%20of%20the%20%E2%80%9CMutual%20Exclusivity%20Theory%E2%80%9D%20which%20had%20its%20genesis%20in%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.casemine.com%2Fjudgement%2Fin%2F5609aae9e4b014971140b32d%5C%22%3E%3Ci%3EA.%20K.%20Gopalan%20vs%20State%20of%20Madras%3C%2Fi%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20and%20which%20had%20been%20followed%20for%2020%20years%20prior%20to%20this%20case.%20The%20Supreme%20Court%20held%20in%20%3Ci%3ECooper%3C%2Fi%3E%20that%20it%20could%20not%20dismiss%20a%20petition%20that%20unequivocally%20demonstrated%20that%20people%E2%80%99s%20fundamental%20rights%20were%20being%20violated%2C%20based%20solely%20on%20technicalities.%20Just%20because%20a%20legislative%20measure%20violated%20a%20corporation%E2%80%99s%20rights%2C%20the%20court%20does%20not%20lack%20jurisdiction%20to%20defend%20the%20shareholder%20rights%20of%20the%20firm%2C%20the%20court%20held.%3Cspan%3E%C2%A0%20%C2%A0%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EIn%20%3Ci%3ECooper%2C%20%3C%2Fi%3Ethe%20court%20specifically%20overruled%20%3Ci%3EGopalan%20%3C%2Fi%3Eand%20declared%20that%20even%20if%20a%20law%20satisfied%20the%20requirement%20of%20Article%2031(2)%20(dealing%20with%20compulsory%20acquisition%20of%20property)%20it%20has%20to%20satisfy%20the%20requirement%20of%20Article%2019(1)(f)%20(right%20to%20property)%20too.%3Cspan%3E%C2%A0%3C%2Fspan%3EArticle%2031%20and%20Article%2019(1)(f)%20were%20repealed%20in%20the%20post-Emergency%20period.%20Thus%20the%20court%20held%20that%20if%20a%20tribunal%20is%20authorised%20by%20an%20Act%20to%20determine%20compensation%20for%20property%20compulsorily%20acquired%20without%20hearing%20the%20owner%20of%20the%20property%2C%20the%20Act%20would%20be%20liable%20to%20be%20struck%20down%20under%20Article%2019(1)(f).%3Cspan%3E%C2%A0%20%C2%A0%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EPreviously%2C%20on%20the%20basis%20of%20the%20judgment%20in%20%3Ci%3EGopalan%3C%2Fi%3E%2C%20it%20was%20held%20in%20a%20long%20line%20of%20cases%20that%20each%20article%20guaranteed%20a%20distinct%20Fundamental%20Right.%3Cspan%3E%C2%A0%3C%2Fspan%3EIt%20meant%20that%20the%20legislation%20to%20be%20examined%20must%20be%20directly%20in%20respect%20of%20the%20rights%20mentioned%20in%20that%20sub-clause.%20But%20%3Ci%3ECooper%3C%2Fi%3E%20changed%20this%20interpretation%20on%20the%20ground%20that%20if%20an%20act%20of%20the%20executive%2C%20or%20a%20law%20is%20liable%20to%20be%20tested%20in%20terms%20of%20more%20than%20one%20Fundamental%20Right%2C%20it%20is%20better%20for%20the%20citizen.%3Cspan%3E%C2%A0%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EIn%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.casemine.com%2Fjudgement%2Fin%2F5609abd1e4b014971140d6b0%5C%22%3E%3Ci%3EManeka%20Gandhi%20vs%20Union%20of%20India%20And%20Another%3C%2Fi%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%20(1978)%2C%20the%20petitioner%3Ci%3E%20%3C%2Fi%3Ealleged%20that%20the%20order%20denying%20her%20passport%20violated%20Article%2014%20and%20that%20the%20right%20to%20travel%20abroad%20was%20under%20the%20broad%20definition%20of%20personal%20freedom%20guaranteed%20by%20Article%2021.%20The%20court%20ruled%20that%20there%20is%20a%20special%20connection%20between%20the%20provisions%20of%20Articles%2014%2C%2019%2C%20and%2021.%20As%20a%20result%2C%20a%20law%20that%20restricts%20someone%E2%80%99s%20%E2%80%9Cpersonal%20liberty%E2%80%9D%20must%20also%20pass%20the%20constitutional%20tests%20of%20Article%2019%20and%20Article%2014%20in%20addition%20to%20Article%2021%2C%20and%20thus%20the%20court%20affirmed%20the%20idea%20that%20the%20various%20fundamental%20rights%20interact%20with%20each%20other%20and%20can%20not%20be%20interpreted%20in%20isolation.%3Cspan%3E%C2%A0%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThe%20%3Ci%3EManeka%20Gandhi%20%3C%2Fi%3Ecase%20thus%20first%20gave%20birth%20to%20the%20doctrine%20of%20the%20Golden%20Triangle%20which%20represents%20the%20interconnectedness%20and%20dependency%20of%20these%20three%20fundamental%20rights.%20These%20three%20articles%20complement%20one%20another%20and%20offer%20a%20framework%20for%20defending%20the%20fundamental%20liberties%20and%20rights%20of%20every%20Indian%20citizen.%20%3Cspan%3E%C2%A0%20%C2%A0%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%20%3Cp%3EThe%20%3Ci%3EKedar%20Nath%20Singh%20%3C%2Fi%3Ebench%20did%20not%20have%20the%20benefit%20of%20applying%20these%20later%20developments%20in%20law%20to%20test%20the%20constitutionality%20of%20Section%20124A%2C%20and%20therefore%2C%20its%20judgment%20deserves%20to%20be%20reconsidered%20and%20set%20aside%20by%20a%20larger%20bench.%3Cspan%3E%C2%A0%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%22%2C%22published%22%3A1696247115000%2C%22visual%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.t